Suicide in the 21st Century

In 2017, a man whom I considered one of the greatest musicians of all time and author, or co-author, of a number of songs that had become the soundtrack of my life, died in suicide. Many were shocked, and many miss him today. In 2018, a man whose TV programs repeatedly kept me in a state of respect towards, and fascination about, the diversity of the world, died in suicide. Many were shocked, and many miss him today.

Close to 800000 less-famous people die due to suicide every year, according to WHO. I looked at the WHO Suicide Statistics to see where the world as a whole is heading.

Is it getting better or worse? You will see my answer below.

def avg():
    df_country=df.groupby(["country"],as_index=False)["population","suicides_no"].sum()
    df_country["suicides_per_100k"]=df_country["suicides_no"]/(df_country["population"]/100000)
    df_country["Average_suicide"] = df_country["suicides_no"]/31  
    g=df_country.sort_values("Average_suicide").tail(10)
    return(g)

def all_countries():
    df_country=df.groupby(["country","year"],as_index=False)["population","suicides_no"].sum()
    
    g = sns.FacetGrid(df_country, col="country", col_wrap=3, height=10)
    g = g.map(plt.plot, "year", "suicides_no", marker=".")
    return(g)
all_countries()

In [11]:
def suicides_per_100k():
    df_country=df.groupby(["country"],as_index=False)["population","suicides_no"].sum()
    df_country["suicides_per_100k"]=df_country["suicides_no"]/(df_country["population"]/100000)
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,20))
    plt.axvline(df_country["suicides_per_100k"].mean(), color='r', linestyle='--')
    df_country.sort_values('suicides_per_100k',inplace=True)
    sns.barplot(y=df_country["country"], x=df_country["suicides_per_100k"])
    plt.xlabel('No. of suicides per 100k')
    plt.ylabel('Countries')
    plt.title('Total No. of Suicides per country from 1985 to 2016')
    return(plt.show())
suicides_per_100k()

Insights :-

Lithuania’s rate has been highest by a large margin: > 40 suicides per 100k (per year)

Russian Federation rate has been second highest > 30 suicides per 100k (per year)

    df_country.sort_values('suicides_no',inplace=True)

def past_ten_years():
    df_country=df.groupby(["country","year","sex"],as_index=False)["population","suicides_no"].sum()
    df_s=df_country[df_country["year"] > 2005]
    stage = df_s.loc[df_country['country'].isin(["Mexico","Republic of Korea","France","Japan","Russian Federation","United States","Brazil"])]
    
    
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
    plt.axvline(stage["suicides_no"].mean(), color='r', linestyle='--')
    stage.sort_values('suicides_no',inplace=True)
    sns.barplot(y=stage["country"], x=stage["suicides_no"],hue=stage["sex"])
    plt.xlabel('No. of suicides')
    plt.ylabel('Countries')
    plt.title('Total No. of Suicides per country from 2006 to 2016')
    return(plt.show())
past_ten_years()

    Japan = df_s.loc[df_country['country'].isin(["Japan"])]

    mexico = df_s.loc[df_country['country'].isin(["Mexico"])]

def age():
    df_country=df.groupby(["country","year","age"],as_index=False)["population","suicides_no"].sum()
    df_s=df_country[df_country["year"] > 2005]
    stage = df_country.loc[df_country['country'].isin(["Mexico","Republic of Korea","France","Japan","Russian Federation","United States","Brazil"])]

    plt.ylabel('Countries')
    plt.title('Total No. of Suicides per country from 2006 to 2016')
    return(plt.show())

def overall():
    df_country=df.groupby(["country","year","sex"],as_index=False)["population","suicides_no"].sum()
    df_s=df_country[df_country["year"] > 2005]
    stage = df_country.loc[df_country['country'].isin(["Mexico","Republic of Korea","France","Japan","Russian Federation","United States","Brazil"])]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
    g = sns.lineplot(y="suicides_no", x="year",hue="sex", data=stage)
    plt.ylabel('Suicides No.')
    plt.title('Overall Suicide Trend in Data')
    
    return(g)
overall()

def gdp():
    df_gdp = df.groupby(["country","year","gdp_per_capita ($)"],as_index=False)["population","suicides_no"].sum()
    df_gdp["suicides_per_100k"] = df_gdp["suicides_no"]/(df_country["population"]/100000)
    sns.pairplot(df_gdp, x_vars=['suicides_per_100k'], y_vars=["gdp_per_capita ($)"], height=6, aspect=2, kind='reg')
    X = df_gdp["gdp_per_capita ($)"].values.reshape(-1,1)
    y = df_gdp["suicides_per_100k"]
    from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
    lm = LinearRegression()
    lm.fit(X,y)
    print(lm.intercept_)
    print(lm.coef_)
    print("Y = {}".format(lm.coef_),"X + {}".format(lm.intercept_))
gdp()    

2136.2286117616113
[-0.03972663]
Y = [-0.03972663] X + 2136.2286117616113

Insights :-

A weak relation, as can be seen in the above graph; let's evaluate.

X = GDP per Capita ($)

Y = Suicides per 100k

Y = -0.039*X + 2136; meaning with 2136$ increase in gdp per capita, there are additional one suicide per 100K population

Not a very good regresssion, as correaltion is very weak.
